      "role": "user",
      "content": "calling it \"a myth\" sounds a bit strong though. what about the people who actually live in those areas and feel the impact on their day to day? it feels like you're dismissing their lived experience just to stick to an economic theory. don't you think there's a valid way to look at the downsides if we aren't just talking about \"net\" numbers?",
